    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl>Morelli in <ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>216</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>102820</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#parisipresicce2007a"/><citedRange/></bibl> and 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#luni2014b"/>, pp. <citedRange>129, 133</citedRange></bibl> (circumstances of find).</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Kyrana"><name nymRef="#Κυράνα"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Κυρά</supplied>ν<unclear>α</unclear></name></persName> 
                    <lb n="2"/><space extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <persName type="divine" ref="#Aphrodite"><name nymRef="#Ἀφροδίτα"><unclear>Ἀφρο</unclear>δίτας</name></persName> 
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                 <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Cyrè</supplied>ne. <supplied reason="subaudible">Autel d'</supplied> Aphrodite.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Cyre</supplied>ne. <supplied reason="subaudible">Altar of</supplied> Aphrodite.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Cire</supplied>ne. <supplied reason="subaudible">Altare di</supplied> Aphrodite.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This was published by Morelli without illustration and only the printed layout informs us. The reading seems to be very uncertain and a nominative 
                    at line 1 would be very surprising. Such altars also bear names at the genitive of men who are whorshippers of the mentioned god. The shift in the 
                    layout might sustain this idea. So we cannot exclude a personal name ending with <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ας</foreign>. Moreover, as the alpha itself 
                    was unclear to Morelli, the whole remains very obscure.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
